\f4\ltrch\u9876?\u-497?\f1\lang1033  \f0 Lincoln, Total War, and the Lieber Code\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
\f0\ltrch\lang1033 In April 1863, President Abraham Lincoln approved General Orders No. 100, also known as the Lieber Code, drafted by legal scholar Francis Lieber1\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
.\par
\par
\f0\ltrch\lang1033 The Lieber Code was the first formal codification of the laws of war in the U.S., and it explicitly allowed for harsh measures\f1\lang1037\emdash\f0\lang1033 including destruction of civilian property\f1\lang1037\emdash\f0\lang1033 if deemed militarily necessary.\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
\par
\f0\ltrch\lang1033 Though it also prohibited wanton cruelty, it gave commanders wide latitude to interpret necessity, which opened the door to what we now call total war.\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
\par
\f3\ltrch\u-10179?\u-8923?\f1\lang1033  \f0 Sherman\f1\lang1037\rquote\f0\lang1033 s March and the Burning of Atlanta\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
\f0\ltrch\lang1033 In November 1864, General William Tecumseh Sherman launched his infamous March to the Sea, from Atlanta to Savannah2\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
.\par
\par
\f0\ltrch\lang1033 His troops followed a \f1\lang1037\ldblquote\f0\lang1033 scorched earth\f1\lang1037\rdblquote\f0\lang1033  policy, destroying railroads, crops, factories, and civilian infrastructure to break the South\f1\lang1037\rquote\f0\lang1033 s will to fight2\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
3\par
.\par
\par
\f0\ltrch\lang1033 The burning of Atlanta and the devastation of Georgia were not rogue actions\f1\lang1037\emdash\f0\lang1033 they were strategically sanctioned and aligned with Lincoln\f1\lang1037\rquote\f0\lang1033 s war aims3\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
.\par
\par
\f3\ltrch\u-10180?\u-8273?\f1\lang1033  \f0 Political Context: Lincoln\f1\lang1037\rquote\f0\lang1033 s Reelection\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
\f0\ltrch\lang1033 By mid-1864, Lincoln feared he would lose the election to George McClellan, who favored a negotiated peace with the Confederacy.\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
\par
\f0\ltrch\lang1033 Sherman\f1\lang1037\rquote\f0\lang1033 s capture of Atlanta in September 1864 was a turning point that boosted Northern morale and helped secure Lincoln\f1\lang1037\rquote\f0\lang1033 s reelection.\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
\par
\f0\ltrch\lang1033 The timing and intensity of Sherman\f1\lang1037\rquote\f0\lang1033 s campaign were not coincidental\f1\lang1037\emdash\f0\lang1033 they were part of a broader strategy to end the war before political momentum shifted.\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
\par
\f4\ltrch\u-10178?\u-8723?\f1\lang1033  \f0 Constitutional Irony\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
\f0\ltrch\lang1033 You\f1\lang1037\rquote\f0\lang1033 re right to point out the Declaration of Independence\f1\lang1037\rquote\f0\lang1033 s language about the right to alter or abolish tyrannical government.\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
\par
\f0\ltrch\lang1033 The Confederacy used that very logic to justify secession\f1\lang1037\emdash\f0\lang1033 while Lincoln\f1\lang1037\rquote\f0\lang1033 s administration rejected it, arguing that the Union was indivisible and that secession was unconstitutional.\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
\par
\f4\ltrch\u-10178?\u-8728?\f1\lang1033  \f0 So, Was It About Slavery?\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
\f0\ltrch\lang1033 Slavery was the central cause of secession\f1\lang1037\emdash\f0\lang1033 but not the initial rallying cry of the Union war effort.\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
\par
\f0\ltrch\lang1033 Lincoln\f1\lang1037\rquote\f0\lang1033 s Emancipation Proclamation came in 1863\f1\lang1037\emdash\f0\lang1033 two years into the war\f1\lang1037\emdash\f0\lang1033 and was as much a strategic move as a moral one.\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
\par
\f0\ltrch\lang1033 The North\f1\lang1037\rquote\f0\lang1033 s war aims evolved: from preserving the Union \f8\u8594?\f0\lang1033  to ending slavery \f8\u8594?\f0\lang1033  to total military subjugation.\f7\rtlch\lang1037\par
\par
